Churn Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis & Retention Insights

Project Overview

Click to expand project overview

TL;DR: Retention is strong (83%), but churn correlates most strongly with recent engagement, usage frequency, and driving behavior patterns. These insights help inform targeted retention strategy and future churn-prediction modeling.

This project explores driver engagement and churn behavior using Waze usage data. The goal is to identify trends that distinguish retained users from churned users and uncover behavioral signals that may predict churn risk. Insights from this exploratory work help inform future modeling decisions and guide product strategy around user retention.

Data Integrity & Preparation

Overall, the dataset is reliable and well-structured for analysis. Most variables are complete, numeric fields load cleanly, and no obvious data corruption is present. The only missing data occurs in the label column, which contains the churn outcome. These rows were excluded to ensure the analysis remained meaningful and accurate. Outliers were identified in several engagement metrics; however, these reflect genuine high-usage behavior rather than data entry errors. Where appropriate, extreme values were capped at the 95th percentile to reduce their disproportionate impact on summary statistics.

Key Findings

User Engagement Is Highly Skewed

Many engagement features, including sessions, drives, and total distance driven, exhibit strong right-skew. This suggests a small portion of extremely active users while the majority demonstrate moderate usage. This is important context for both modeling and retention strategies.

Churn vs. Retention Levels

Roughly 17% of users churned, while 83% were retained. Retention is strong overall, but the churned segment is still large enough to warrant proactive intervention strategies.

Behavioral Patterns Matter

Several metrics appear meaningfully associated with churn likelihood:

  • Users with higher recent engagement are less likely to churn.

  • Users with longer tenure still churn, though at slightly lower rates than newer users.

  • Driving frequency and variety of app interactions also show trends worth deeper investigation.

These are not causal conclusions but meaningful signals that should influence both business and modeling direction.

Questions Raised for Further Exploration

This exploratory work suggests several next steps:

  • How does time since last activity relate to churn probability?

  • Do geographic or driving context factors influence churn?

  • Are there behavioral sub-segments (e.g., commuters vs. infrequent drivers) with distinct churn risks?

  • Which in-app behaviors most effectively predict long-term retention?

These insights would be especially valuable for designing targeted engagement strategies.

Product Implications

From a business perspective, these findings can help Waze:

  • Reinforce engagement habits among moderately active users before they drift.

  • Support and reward long-distance / high-usage drivers.

  • Recognize that even long-tenured users remain at churn risk and require continued engagement.

  • Inform the development of churn-prediction models and retention interventions.


Imports and Data Loading

To begin the analysis, the dataset was loaded into a Pandas dataframe and core analytical libraries were imported, including NumPy, Matplotlib, and Seaborn for visualization. The dataset is pre-cleaned and loaded automatically, allowing the focus to remain on analysis rather than file preparation.

The dataset includes detailed user behavior attributes such as activity levels, driving frequency, app engagement metrics, time since onboarding, and churn status. These fields form the foundation for understanding which behavioral signals differentiate retained users from churned users.

Data Quality Review & Preparation Strategy

Before conducting deeper analysis, the dataset was evaluated to ensure reliability, completeness, and suitability for churn analysis. All fields, except the ID column, directly describe user behavior and engagement patterns relevant to retention outcomes, while the label column serves as the churn target variable.

Initial validation confirmed that:

  • The dataset is structurally sound and suitable for modeling
  • Only the label column contains missing values. These rows were removed to maintain analytical integrity
  • Numerical features display meaningful right-skew driven by real high-engagement users, aligning with expected real-world behavior

Outliers were reviewed using summary statistics, distribution visualizations, and interquartile range checks. Because these values represent genuine heavy-usage behavior rather than data entry errors, they were retained. Capping was only applied in limited cases to stabilize summary interpretation.

Engagement Behavior Analysis

To better understand how users interact with Waze, visual exploratory analysis was performed on key engagement metrics such as session frequency, trips driven, navigation behavior, and in-app activity. These visualizations help identify distribution shape, behavioral clusters, and potential outliers, which is essential context before modeling churn.

The sessions variable shows a strong right-skewed distribution, meaning:

  • Most users use Waze moderately.
  • A small group of users log exceptionally high session counts.
  • Around 50% of users have 56 sessions or fewer in the observed period.
  • The extreme values visible in the boxplot likely represent highly engaged power users, not data errors.

Why this matters:

Understanding this skew is important. These high-engagement users contribute significantly to retention stability, while moderate/low-engagement users may be more vulnerable to churn.

  • The median user opened the app ~16 days out of the month (about every other day).

  • Users with few or zero activity days may be at higher churn risk, potentially due to:
    • reduced driving needs,
    • switching to competitors,
    • or losing trust/value in the app.

The diversity in distribution highlights potential distinct user segments Waze could target differently - casual drivers, habitual commuters, and fully disengaged users.

    • seasonal driving behavior
    • temporary inactivity
    • or early-stage churn risk

This discrepancy between opening the app and actually driving is important. It suggests user intent and engagement cant be understood by a single metric alone. These findings should be revisited when analyzing churn predictors and user segmentation.

Driving Days vs. Activity Days

Understanding how often users open the app vs. how often they actually drive.

Since both driving_days and activity_days measure behavior across the same monthly time window, comparing them together helps reveal meaningful differences between engagement and actual driving behavior.

In[27]:
# Histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
sns.histplot(df['driving_days'], bins=range(0,33), color='red', alpha=0.6, discrete=True)
sns.histplot(df['activity_days'], bins=range(0,33), color='blue', alpha=0.6, discrete=True)

plt.title("Driving Days vs Activity Days")
plt.xlabel("Days")
plt.ylabel("User Count")
plt.legend(['Driving Days', 'Activity Days'])
plt.show()

This visualization highlights an interesting behavioral pattern:

  • Most users opened the app and drove on a similar number of days
  • However, there are:
    • More users who didnt drive at all than users who didnt open the app at all
    • More users who opened the app nearly every day than users who drove nearly every day

In other words:

  • Many people open Waze without driving
  • Very few people drive every single day

This makes sense in real-world behavior. Users may open Waze to:

  • Check traffic conditions
  • Plan routes without starting a trip
  • Update preferences
  • Or simply out of habit

So although the two features are related, they clearly capture different user behaviors.

Why this matters:

This distinction is valuable for churn analysis:

  • Activity Days reflects overall engagement / app habit
  • Driving Days reflects functional app usage

Users with strong app-opening habits but fewer driving days may still be retained. Users who rarely open the app at all are at higher churn risk.

This suggests that retention is not driven purely by driving behavior, but also by how integrated Waze is in users' routine.

This plot reveals a very clean behavioral boundary:

  • Users cannot have more driving days than activity days
  • Every driving day must also be an app-usage day
  • The data perfectly respects this rule, indicating strong data reliability and logical consistency

This creates a triangular pattern:

  • Along the diagonal: users who open the app mostly only when they drive
  • Above the diagonal: users who open the app more frequently than they drive

Notably, many users cluster above the diagonal, meaning:

  • Users frequently open Waze even when they arent driving
  • The app is being used as a planning, checking, or information tool, not just for navigation

Why this matters:

This reinforces an earlier finding:

  • Activity Days captures user engagement habit
  • Driving Days captures mobility and trip behavior

A user may:

  • Be highly engaged (opens app frequently)
  • But not necessarily drive frequently

From a churn perspective:

  • High activity_days suggests habitual app reliance strong retention indicator
  • Low activity_days with low driving_days may signal disengagement risk

This makes activity_days a particularly valuable feature for future churn modeling.

Retention by device

This visualization compares churn and retention between Android and iPhone users to determine whether device type plays a meaningful role in churn behavior.

A few clear patterns emerge:

  • iPhone users make up a larger portion of the dataset overall (consistent with the earlier pie chart showing more iPhone users)

  • However, the ratio of retained vs churned users remains very similar across both platforms

In other words:

  • Both Android and iPhone users churn at nearly the same rate
  • Device type does not appear to be a meaningful driver of churn in this dataset

This is an important finding, because it rules out a common assumption:

  • Performance differences
  • Platform experience differences
  • OS-specific UX differences

do not appear to be significantly impacting user retention.

Why this matters:

From a product and strategy perspective:

  • Retention efforts should not be segmented by device platform
  • Resources are better spent focusing on behavioral engagement signals (e.g., sessions, activity days, navigation behavior)
  • Device can safely be treated as a context variable, not a primary churn predictor

This supports the earlier insight that churn is behavior-driven rather than platform-driven.

Retention by Kilometers Driven per Driving Day

This metric looks at how far users typically drive on the days they actually use Waze. To analyze this fairly, the data was cleaned to remove impossible values (e.g., users with 0 driving days producing infinite distances, and extremely unrealistic values above ~1,200 km/day).

In[41]:
# Creation of `km_per_driving_day` column and inf value clean-up
df['km_per_driving_day'] = df['driven_km_drives']/df['driving_days']
df['km_per_driving_day'] = df['km_per_driving_day'].replace([np.inf],0)

# Stacked Histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
sns.histplot(
    data=df[df['km_per_driving_day'] <= 1200],
    x='km_per_driving_day',
    hue='label',
    bins=range(0,1200,50),
    multiple='fill',
    alpha=0.8
    )

plt.title("Retention vs Churn by KM per Driving Day")
plt.xlabel("Kilometers per Day")
plt.ylabel("% of Users")
plt.show()

Once unrealistic values were removed, a clear pattern emerged:

  • Most users typically drive between ~100 km and 600 km per day on days they use Waze
  • Users who drive shorter distances per day are more likely to remain retained
  • As average daily distance increases, the churn rate becomes noticeably higher

In simpler terms:

  • Light-to-moderate Waze drivers tend to stay
  • Heavy-distance drivers are more likely to churn

This aligns with previous findings that:

  • Median distance per driving day was much higher for churned users (~700 km)
  • Retained users drove significantly less per day (~290 km)

Why this matters:

This is a high-impact behavioral signal:

  • Long-distance drivers may experience fatigue, cost burden, or decreased reliance on navigation on familiar long routes
  • These users might stop depending on Waze after initial route learning
  • Waze may need different retention strategies for long-distance users vs typical commuters

From a product perspective, this suggests opportunities such as:

  • Features tailored to professional/long-distance drivers
  • Mileage-driven rewards or engagement nudges
  • Route optimization highlights to maintain perceived value

How frequently users actually drive with Waze in a month, and how this relates to churn likelihood.

# Stacked Histogram
df_clean = df.dropna(subset=['label'])

plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))

sns.histplot(
    data=df_clean,
    x='driving_days',
    hue='label',
    bins=range(0,32,1),
    multiple='fill',
    discrete=True
)

plt.title("Churn Rate by Number of Driving Days")
plt.xlabel("Driving Days (per Month)")
plt.ylabel("Proportion of Users")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This visualization shows a very clear behavioral signal:

  • Users who barely drove at all in the last month are significantly more likely to churn
    • Churn rate is highest when driving days are between 03 days
  • As driving frequency increases, churn steadily declines
    • Moderate users (1020 driving days/month) show strong retention
  • Heavy drivers have almost no churn
    • Users with 30 driving days did not churn at all in this dataset

This pattern suggests that recent real-world app dependency is a strong retention anchor. Users who actively rely on Waze for frequent driving are far less likely to leave.

Why This Matters:

This is a powerful product insight:

  • Low driving activity = churn risk
  • Consistent driving behavior = retention stability
  • Engagement is not just opening the app, its functional, purposeful usage

This can guide strategy in multiple areas:

  • Target re-engagement campaigns at low-driving users early
  • Encourage light users to build driving habits (nudges, tips, reminders)
  • Prioritize features that provide long-term daily driving value

Recent Activity as a Share of Lifetime Engagement

Understanding how intensely users engaged with Waze in the most recent month relative to their entire lifetime usage.

This chart reveals an important, and surprising, pattern:

  • A very large portion of users logged over 40% of their lifetime sessions in just the last month
  • Engagement is heavily concentrated recently rather than evenly spread over time
  • This suggests that many users have suddenly become highly active very recently

At the same time, when we compare this against user tenure, things become unexpected.

Who Are These Sudden Power Users?

To investigate further, we filtered only users whose recent month accounted for 40% of their lifetime Waze usage, and examined how long theyve been on the platform.

In[44]:

Even though these users showed unusually high activity in the most recent month:

  • Their time since account creation is spread almost uniformly
  • Many of them have been on Waze for multiple years
  • This means the spike is not just from brand-new users
  • Long-time users suddenly became extremely active

That makes this behavior particularly intriguing.

Why This Matters:

This pattern suggests there may have been:

  • A recent external trigger (e.g., policy change, travel season, fuel crises, commuting changes)
  • A successful product/feature rollout that increased dependency
  • Market or regional factors (e.g., road closures, migration, tourism, weather events)
  • Or potentially data logging changes that impacted session tracking

Either way, this is a meaningful behavioral anomaly worth business investigation.

Product Insight Opportunity

This finding can help Waze:

  • Identify what caused the spike in recent heavy usage
  • Determine whether it correlates with retention improvements
  • Understand whether similar events can be intentionally replicated
  • Evaluate whether churn risk decreases following such activity bursts

Handling Outliers

Several engagement metrics in this dataset (e.g., sessions, drives, distance, and duration) follow right-skewed distributions. The extreme high values are not likely to be data errors. Rather, they appear to represent very heavy power users. However, extremely large values can still distort statistical summaries and model behavior.

To reduce their influence while preserving meaningful signal, I applied a 95th-percentile capping strategy (winsorization):

  • For each selected numeric feature,
  • Compute the value at the 95th percentile
  • Replace values above this threshold with the 95th-percentile cutoff
  • All other values remain unchanged

This approach preserves distribution shape and rank relationships while preventing a few users from dominating the analysis.

In[45]:
def percentile95(col):
    cap = np.percentile(col, 95)
    return np.where(col > cap, cap, col)

df['sessions'] = percentile95(df['sessions'])
df['drives'] = percentile95(df['drives'])
df['total_sessions'] = percentile95(df['total_sessions'])
df['driven_km_drives'] = percentile95(df['driven_km_drives'])
df['duration_minutes_drives'] = percentile95(df['duration_minutes_drives'])

df.describe()

Additional Behavioral Insights

To better understand the drivers behind churn, the following EDA explores how recent usage and user tenure relate to retention outcomes.

In[46]:
# Churn vs. Recent Activity
df_clean = df.dropna(subset=['label'])

plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
sns.histplot(
    data=df_clean,
    x='percent_sessions_in_last_month',
    hue='label',
    bins=range(0,101,10),
    multiple='fill'
)

plt.title("Churn Rate by Percentage of Lifetime Sessions in Last Month")
plt.xlabel("Percent of Lifetime Sessions in Last Month (%)")
plt.ylabel("Proportion of Users")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Even though users vary widely in how much they used the app in the most recent month, the churn rate remains fairly stable across most ranges. This suggests that:

  • Simply using the app a lot in the last month does not automatically reduce churn
  • Heavy recent usage does not guarantee loyalty
  • Other behavioral or contextual factors likely play a stronger role in whether a user leaves or stays

In short, recency alone is not a strong churn predictor.

In[47]:
# Tenure vs Churn
plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
sns.histplot(
    data=df_clean,
    x='n_days_after_onboarding',
    hue='label',
    bins=40,
    multiple='fill'
)

plt.title("Churn Rate by Time Since Onboarding")
plt.xlabel("Days Since Onboarding")
plt.ylabel("Proportion of Users")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Here, a clearer trend emerges:

  • Users who have been with the app longer churn less
  • Newer users are more likely to leave
  • Retention stabilizes significantly after extended periods of continued use

This indicates that tenure is strongly linked to loyalty. Once users integrate Waze into their routine over time, they are far less likely to churn.

Conclusion

This exploratory analysis builds a strong behavioral understanding of churn within Wazes user base:

  • Monthly engagement volume explains some churn behavior
  • Recent spikes in usage do not meaningfully impact churn on their own
  • Longer user tenure is one of the strongest stabilizing factors for retention

From here, the next step is to transition from descriptive analysis to predictive modeling. This would involve building a churn prediction model, validating key drivers, and partnering with product stakeholders to turn insights into targeted retention strategies.
